Title: When the Data Grows Up Before You Do

Subtitle: On missing variables, evolving surveys, and what to do when your dataset is no longer the same person you met in 2017.

Somewhere between naptime and the 10:00 p.m. writing window, I found myself staring at a spreadsheet that reminded me, strangely, of my toddler’s closet: full of items that no longer fit, a few shiny new pieces, and that one beloved thing that’s somehow been around for years, still functional, still too precious to toss.

The spreadsheet in question was my career pathways dataset—three waves of survey responses from PhD alumni across the country. It had grown, evolved. Learned new words. Shed old ones. It no longer asked the same questions in 2019 as it did in 2017 or 2018. And like a mom realizing she has no idea what size shoe her child wears, I had to confront an unsettling truth: my variables no longer lined up.

The problem isn’t new. Anyone working with longitudinal data knows this moment. Variables disappear. Others arrive with fresh ambition—Resilience, Rigor, Risk-taking—but they show up late to the party, uninvited by the earlier cohorts. They don’t have counterparts, and no one saved them a seat.

So you’re left asking: Do I welcome the new guests and ignore the awkwardness? Or do I send them back home, pretending we’re all still wearing the same shoes we wore in 2017?

Option One: Pretend Nothing Changed

The cleanest solution—the one favored by statisticians who sleep well at night—is to drop the new items altogether. If you’re comparing across years, you can’t compare what doesn’t exist. No Rigor in 2017? Then no Rigor in your analysis. Done. Simple.

Except it’s not simple. It’s honest, but it’s also a little like refusing to teach your younger child new words because your oldest didn’t know them at the same age.

Option Two: Keep the Data, Accept the Gaps

Then there’s the option that feels a little more maternal: make room. Keep Resilience, Rigor, and Risk-taking for 2019. Let them stay. Just acknowledge they weren’t there before, and don’t expect them to pretend otherwise.

This means living with missing values. Maybe you impute. Maybe you don’t. Maybe you just say: not everyone was asked, and that’s okay. This is the path for those of us who don’t need our models to be perfect, just honest.

Option Three: Stitch a Story Together

But the option I love—the one that feels truest to how I live and work and parent and write—is to stitch something new from the pieces I have. To make meaning even when the seams show.

Resilience didn’t exist in 2017, but Stress tolerance did. Can they hold hands? Maybe together they form a composite—a sort of "emotional fortitude" score. Same with Rigor and Attention to detail. Not twins, but close cousins. In 2017, I only had detail. In 2019, I have both. So I average them. I build bridges.

I tell the data: I see you. I know you’ve changed. And I’ll meet you where you are.

A Note on Career Motivation (and the Stories We Tell)

Here’s where the survey language gets philosophical. In 2017–18, alumni told us their careers were motivated by “Professional interests.” In 2019, the phrase shifted: now it’s “Intellectual challenge.”

It’s tempting to treat these as the same. They’re not. Not really.

“Professional interests” is what you say at a networking event. “Intellectual challenge” is what you whisper at midnight, after your kids are finally asleep and you’re still thinking about that one perfect sentence you haven’t written yet.

Still, for analysis, I unified them—calling it InterestMotivated—and z-scored within year, just in case the words meant something slightly different over time.

Because language changes. Motives shift. We grow into new questions.

Why I’m Building RIASEC Scores at 11 p.m. on a Tuesday

To make sense of all this, I built composite scores based on the RIASEC framework—Investigative, Social, Enterprising, Conventional, Realistic, and Artistic. I wanted to reduce the noise. To see patterns. To find clarity inside the chaos.

It’s like packing a diaper bag for the day: if you try to carry everything, you’ll break your back. But if you know the essentials, you can go far.

Each RIASEC score is a little bundle of variables:

Investigative: Research activities, love of analytical thinking, and craving for intellectual challenge.

Social: Teaching, service, valuing cooperation.

Enterprising: Managing people, leading initiatives, and—yes—risk-taking.

Conventional: Coordination, detail, and the sweet, stable pull of job security.

We skip Realistic and Artistic for now—not because they’re unimportant, but because this dataset doesn’t quite know how to speak their language.

What It All Means (For Now)

In the end, working with imperfect data is like parenting: you do your best with what you’ve got. You make adjustments. You listen closely. You try not to panic when things don’t line up neatly.

The 2019 survey isn’t better or worse—it’s just different. Like me. Like my kids. Like the questions we ask ourselves as we move through this strange, nonlinear thing called a career.

And maybe the real story isn’t about the variables that stayed the same, but the ones that changed—and why.
